  "prompt_text": "Calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin.",
  "response_text": "To calculate the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin, we need to understand that each flip is an independent event with two possible outcomes: heads or tails.\n\nThe total number of possible outcomes when flipping a coin 5 times is \\(2^5 = 32\\), since each flip has 2 possible outcomes and there are 5 flips.\n\nFor exactly 3 heads, we can use the binomial probability formula:\n\n\\[ P(X = k) = \\binom{n}{k} p^k (1-p)^{n-k} \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( n \\) is the number of trials (flips),\n- \\( k \\) is the number of successful outcomes,\n- \\( p \\) is the probability of success on a single trial (heads),\n- \\( \\binom{n}{k} \\) is the binomial coefficient, which represents the number of ways to choose \\( k \\) successes out of \\( n \\) trials.\n\nIn our case:\n- \\( n = 5 \\)\n- \\( k = 3 \\)\n- \\( p = 0.5 \\)\n\nPlugging these values into the formula gives us:\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = \\binom{5}{3} (0.5)^3 (0.5)^{5-3} \\]\n\nFirst, calculate the binomial coefficient:\n\n\\[ \\binom{5}{3} = \\frac{5!}{3!(5-3)!} = \\frac{5!}{3!2!} = \\frac{5 \\times 4}{2 \\times 1} = 10 \\]\n\nNow, substitute back into the formula:\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = 10 \\times (0.5)^3 \\times (0.5)^2 \\]\n\nSimplify the expression:\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = 10 \\times (0.5)^5 \\]\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = 10 \\times \\frac{1}{32} \\]\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = \\frac{10}{32} \\]\n\n\\[ P(X = 3) = \\frac{5}{16} \\]\n\nSo, the probability of getting exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips of a fair coin is \\(\\frac{5}{16}\\).\n\n### Cognitive Engagement Ratings:\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 7\nP (Pattern Recognition): 6\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 5\nQ (Contextual Awareness): 4\nC (Pattern Recognition): 3\nY (Affective Modeling): 2\nF (Flexibility): 1\nD (Depth of Processing): 1\n\n### End of Response",
